.TH "ELEMENT.MOVEBEFORE" "3JS" "September 17, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Element.moveBefore \- Element: moveBefore() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]moveBefore()\f[B]\f[R] method of the \f[CR]Element\f[R]
interface moves a given \f[CR]Node\f[R] inside the invoking node as a
direct child, before a given reference node.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
moveBefore(movedNode, referenceNode)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]movedNode\f[R]
A \f[CR]Node\f[R] representing the node to be moved.
Note that this must be an \f[CR]Element\f[R] or a
\f[CR]CharacterData\f[R] node.
.TP
\f[B]referenceNode\f[R]
A \f[CR]Node\f[R] that \f[CR]movedNode\f[R] will be moved before, or
\f[CR]null\f[R].
If the value is \f[CR]null\f[R], \f[CR]movedNode\f[R] is inserted at the
end of the invoking node\(cqs child nodes.
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]HierarchyRequestError\f[R] \f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown in any of the following situations:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
The specified \f[CR]movedNode\f[R] is not part of the DOM, and you are
trying to move it inside a node that is part of the DOM, or vice versa.
.IP \(bu 2
The specified \f[CR]movedNode\f[R] is an ancestor of the Element
\f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R] is being called on.
.IP \(bu 2
You are trying to move \f[CR]movedNode\f[R] between two different
documents.
.IP \(bu 2
The specified \f[CR]movedNode\f[R] is not an \f[CR]Element\f[R] or
\f[CR]CharacterData\f[R] node.
.RE
.TP
\f[B]NotFoundError\f[R] \f[B]TypeError\f[R]
The specified \f[CR]referenceNode\f[R] is not a child of the node you
are calling \f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R] on, that is, the node you are trying
to move \f[CR]movedNode\f[R] inside.
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R] \f[B]TypeError\f[R]
The second argument was not supplied.
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R] method moves a given node to a new place in
the DOM.
It provides similar functionality to the \f[CR]Node.insertBefore()\f[R]
method, except that it doesn\(cqt remove and then reinsert the node.
This means that the state of the node (which would be reset if moving it
with \f[CR]insertBefore()\f[R] and similar mechanisms) is preserved
after the move.
This includes:
.IP \(bu 2
Animation and transition state.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]<iframe>\f[R] loading state.
.IP \(bu 2
Interactivity states (for example, \f[CR]:focus\f[R] and
\f[CR]:active\f[R]).
.IP \(bu 2
Fullscreen element state.
.IP \(bu 2
Open/close state of popovers.
.IP \(bu 2
Modal state of \f[CR]<dialog>\f[R] elements (modal dialogs will not be
closed).
.PP
The play state of \f[CR]<video>\f[R] and \f[CR]<audio>\f[R] elements is
not included in the above list, as these elements retain their state
when removed and reinserted, regardless of the mechanism used.
.PP
When observing changes to the DOM using a \f[CR]MutationObserver\f[R],
nodes moved with \f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R] will be recorded with a removed
node and an added node.
.SS \f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R] constraints
There are some constraints to be aware of when using
\f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R]:
.IP \(bu 2
It can only work when moving a node within the same document.
.IP \(bu 2
It won\(cqt work if you try to move a node that is not connected to the
DOM to an already connected parent, or vice versa.
.PP
In such cases, \f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R] will fail with a
\f[CR]HierarchyRequestError\f[R] exception.
If the above constraints are requirements for your particular use case,
you should use \f[CR]Node.insertBefore()\f[R] instead, or use
\f[CR]try...catch\f[R] to handle the errors that arise from such cases.
.SS Moving custom elements while preserving state
Each time a custom element\(cqs position in the DOM is updated via
\f[CR]Element.moveBefore()\f[R], or similar methods such as
\f[CR]Node.insertBefore()\f[R], its \f[CR]disconnectedCallback()\f[R]
and \f[CR]connectedCallback()\f[R] lifecycle callbacks are fired.
Since these callbacks are typically used to implement any required
initialization or cleanup code to run at the start or end of the
element\(cqs lifecycle, running them when the element is moved (rather
than removed or inserted) may cause problems with its state.
.PP
You can use the \f[CR]connectedMoveCallback()\f[R] callback to preserve
a custom element\(cqs state.
When using \f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R] to move a custom element,
\f[CR]connectedMoveCallback()\f[R] is run instead of
\f[CR]connectedCallback()\f[R] and \f[CR]disconnectedCallback()\f[R].
.PP
See Moving custom elements for further information.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Basic \f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R] usage
In this demo we illustrate basic usage of \f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R].
.SS HTML
The HTML features an \f[CR]<article>\f[R] element containing a
\f[CR]<div>\f[R] element and two \f[CR]<section>\f[R] elements.
The \f[CR]<div>\f[R] contains a \f[CR]<button>\f[R], which we later use
to move it.
.IP
.EX
<article id=\(dqwrapper\(dq>
  <div id=\(dqmover\(dq>
    <button>Move me!</button>
  </div>
  <section id=\(dqsection1\(dq>
    <h2>Section 1</h2>
  </section>
  <section id=\(dqsection2\(dq>
    <h2>Section 2</h2>
  </section>
</article>
.EE
.SS CSS
We provide some rudimentary styling for the look and feel and spacing of
the boxes, and use flexbox to center their content.
.IP
.EX
section1,
section2,
mover {
  width: 200px;
  height: 80px;
  border: 5px solid rgb(0 0 0 / 0.25);
  margin\-bottom: 10px;
  display: flex;
  align\-items: center;
  justify\-content: center;
}

section1,
section2 {
  background\-color: hotpink;
}

mover {
  background\-color: orange;
}
.EE
.SS JavaScript
In our script, we attach a click event listener to the
\f[CR]<button>\f[R] via \f[CR]addEventListener()\f[R].
When the button is clicked, we check whether the
\f[CR]nextElementSibling\f[R] of our \f[CR]mover\f[R] \f[CR]<div>\f[R]
is the first \f[CR]<section>\f[R] element.
If so, we invoke \f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R] on the \f[CR]wrapper\f[R]
\f[CR]<article>\f[R] and specify to move the \f[CR]<div>\f[R] before the
second \f[CR]<section>\f[R].
If not, we use \f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R] to move the \f[CR]<div>\f[R]
before the first \f[CR]<section>\f[R].
.IP
.EX
const wrapper = document.getElementById(\(dqwrapper\(dq);
const section1 = document.getElementById(\(dqsection1\(dq);
const section2 = document.getElementById(\(dqsection2\(dq);
const mover = document.getElementById(\(dqmover\(dq);
const moveBtn = document.querySelector(\(dqbutton\(dq);

moveBtn.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, () => {
  if (mover.nextElementSibling === section1) {
    wrapper.moveBefore(mover, section2);
  } else {
    wrapper.moveBefore(mover, section1);
  }
});
.EE
.SS Result
The rendered example looks like this:
.PP
Try clicking the \f[CR]<button>\f[R] a few times and note how it toggles
between the two positions.
.SS Demonstrating state preservation
In this demo we provide multiple mechanisms to move a \f[CR]<div>\f[R]
element containing a YouTube embed between two different containers,
demonstrating how \f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R] preserves the play state of
the embed, but the other mechanisms do not.
.SS HTML
The HTML features an \f[CR]<article>\f[R] element containing two
\f[CR]<section>\f[R] elements.
The first \f[CR]<section>\f[R] element contains a \f[CR]<div>\f[R]
element containing the YouTube embed code.
We also have a \f[CR]<div>\f[R] element containing three
\f[CR]<button>\f[R] elements, to which we will add functionality to move
the embed \f[CR]<div>\f[R] between sections via JavaScript later on.
.IP
.EX
<article id=\(dqwrapper\(dq>
  <section id=\(dqsection1\(dq>
    <div id=\(dqmover\(dq>
      <iframe
        width=\(dq300\(dq
        height=\(dq200\(dq
        src=\(dqhttps://www.youtube.com/embed/XvoENpR9cCQ?si=o2i6MvxugD\-O5yyv\(dq
        title=\(dqYouTube video player\(dq
        frameborder=\(dq0\(dq
        allow=\(dqaccelerometer; autoplay; clipboard\-write; encrypted\-media; gyroscope; picture\-in\-picture; web\-share\(dq
        referrerpolicy=\(dqstrict\-origin\-when\-cross\-origin\(dq
        allowfullscreen></iframe>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section id=\(dqsection2\(dq></section>
</article>
<div id=\(dqcontrols\(dq>
  <button id=\(dqmove\-before\(dq>move with <code>moveBefore()</code></button>
  <button id=\(dqinsertbefore\(dq>move with <code>insertBefore()</code></button>
  <button id=\(dqprepend\(dq>move with <code>prepend()</code></button>
</div>
.EE
.SS CSS
We use flexbox for the layout to make the two \f[CR]<section>\f[R]
elements sit side\-by\-side, and space the buttons evenly inside the
\f[CR]controls\f[R] \f[CR]<div>\f[R].
.IP
.EX
wrapper,
controls {
  width: 100%;
  display: flex;
}

wrapper {
  margin\-bottom: 10px;
}

section {
  flex: 1;
  padding: 10px;
}

controls {
  display: flex;
  justify\-content: space\-around;
}

section1 {
  background\-color: hotpink;
}

section2 {
  background\-color: orange;
}

mover {
  max\-width: 100%;
  background\-color: black;
}
.EE
.SS JavaScript
In our script, we attach \f[CR]click\f[R] event listeners to each
\f[CR]<button>\f[R] via \f[CR]addEventListener()\f[R].
When the buttons are clicked, we check which \f[CR]<section>\f[R]
element is the \f[CR]parentElement\f[R] of our embed \f[CR]<div>\f[R],
and then use the relevant function (\f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R],
\f[CR]insertBefore()\f[R], or \f[CR]prepend()\f[R]) to move it inside
the \f[I]other\f[R] \f[CR]<section>\f[R] element.
.IP
.EX
const section1 = document.getElementById(\(dqsection1\(dq);
const section2 = document.getElementById(\(dqsection2\(dq);
const mover = document.getElementById(\(dqmover\(dq);
const moveBeforeBtn = document.getElementById(\(dqmove\-before\(dq);
const insertbeforeBtn = document.getElementById(\(dqinsertbefore\(dq);
const prependBtn = document.getElementById(\(dqprepend\(dq);

moveBeforeBtn.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, () => {
  if (mover.parentElement === section1) {
    section2.moveBefore(mover, null);
  } else {
    section1.moveBefore(mover, null);
  }
});

insertbeforeBtn.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, () => {
  if (mover.parentElement === section1) {
    section2.insertBefore(mover, null);
  } else {
    section1.insertBefore(mover, null);
  }
});

prependBtn.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, () => {
  if (mover.parentElement === section1) {
    section2.prepend(mover);
  } else {
    section1.prepend(mover);
  }
});
.EE
.SS Result
The rendered example looks like this:
.PP
Try playing the YouTube embed and then clicking each \f[CR]<button>\f[R]
a couple of times to toggle the \f[CR]<div>\f[R] element screen position
from left to right.
Note how, in the case of \f[CR]insertBefore()\f[R] and
\f[CR]prepend()\f[R], the embed state is reset after each move so it
needs to be restarted.
However, in the case of \f[CR]moveBefore()\f[R], the state is preserved
after each move.
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Document.moveBefore()\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]DocumentFragment.moveBefore()\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
\f[CR]Node.insertBefore()\f[R]
